In this article, President Obama addresses the issue of the Zika virus and the need for Congress to allocate funding to combat it. He mentions that while Zika is not usually life-threatening, it can have severe consequences for fetuses and children born to infected pregnant women. The President emphasizes the importance of reducing the incidents of Zika and providing guidelines for travel and prevention. He also highlights the need for research and development of a vaccine, which requires funding that is currently stuck in Congress. The President urges Congress to allocate the necessary funds before adjourning and emphasizes that politics should not get in the way of public health emergencies. He concludes by expressing hope that a vaccine can be developed quickly if Congress acts swiftly.